t1275.text: I’ve never been so proud of an Ents dept in the face of adversity - this has been an epic night of triumph.

t1276.text: EVERYTHING that could go wrong went wrong. There were several things that couldn’t have gone wrong which did go wrong. At one point I saw dancers hugging each other mid-routine to keep warm.

t1277.text: It..” We were almost frozen and blown overboard, we had THREE guys holding onto the gazebo over the sound desk to stop it blowing overboard, but they couldn’t call it off because the guests were dancing and loving it all.

t1278.text: .. and refuse to obey my commands. The crowd have danced themselves in a conga line inside and we can stop. The heavens open, we rush to pack up and clear off. It takes me 30mins to defrost. I see one of the hosts in the bar. “The guests LOVED it. They won’t stop talking about..

t1279.text: We ditch the track and play a few songs by ourselves. I’m wearing three layers and a beanie, I can’t feel my fingers, I’m so cold... the horns have walked off, the drummer had half a kit left - I get 3/4’s of the way through the last song before my fingers are frozen...

t1280.text: The tracked music is a disaster, no-one knows what is happening or going on, we all stop playing - pleading with the managers to call it off. The PA is awful, feedback and distortion- still the guests dance and enjoy themselves. My amp cuts out.

t1281.text: The wind blows a cymbal off it’s stand, nearly de-capitating me... the dancers are at risk of hypothermia in their skimpy outfits - but the guests are dancing and enjoying themselves...

t1282.text: Rhythm... the crowd are dancing and partying - no way are we stopping. The wind blows our microphones over, our trombonist sees his sheet music blown everywhere. The music manager is laughing at the chaos unfolding... the crowd are congo-ing

t1283.text: Incredulously, we start playing the disco-based set. 20 secs in, the drummer starts waving his arms - the click is out of synch with the backing track! IT WAS ON THE SAME TRACK!?!?!? We all fall apart trying to stay with the live track while the drummer plays a weird in-between..

t1284.text: “EVERYONE HEAD UP TO THE TOP DECK FOR OUR THEME PARTY!” - groans from us, the party band and the orchestra horn section playing with us. “They’ll turn up, see the weather and go back indoors”. Not a bit of it. A large bunch of guests turn up (hats and coats) to see what’s on.

t1285.text: Everyone turns up, we’re wearing hats, coats, just waiting for the whole thing to be cancelled. Spots of rain are falling from black skies. The ship starts to lurch on the Tasman sea. An announcement from the cruise director (currently indoors, unaware of the weather, I guess?)

t1286.text: We had soundchecked earlier, our drummer said the backing track - we were playing live over the video (massive screen) track - was too loud over the click. “The click is on the same track as the backing, we can’t separate them” - OK, we’ll deal with it.

t1287.text: “It’s a showcase theme night, we’ve promoted the hell out of it, everyone’s looking forward to it” they said. OK, we’ll turn up, it’ll start raining and it will get called off. We turned up, it was 5 degrees and blowing a gale, still no cancellation.

t1288.text: 1. ‘Come to Australia’ they said. ‘It will be hot and sunny’ they said. We sailed from Melbourne under dark, cold skies. “There’s no way they’ll let the deck party go ahead, they’ll move it indoors” they said. We looked out at the black skies and nodded.

t1289.text: Tonight we played the worst/greatest show of my life. I don’t even know how to explain it - an unbelievable perfect storm of triumph over adversity. A maelstrom of technical disasters and yet, unbelievably, public success.
